# React component props

- Do **not** add a separate `interface` (or `type`) for a component’s props unless the same shape must be reused elsewhere (e.g. shared across files, exported API). Prefer an inline object type on the `props` parameter.
- Declare components as `function Name(props: { ... }) { ... }`.
- Do **not** destructure `props` in the parameter list or body for the sole purpose of convenience. Use `props.field` (and `props.children`) so the component’s data flow stays explicit.

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid — extra interface only used here, destructured props
interface CardProps {
  title: string
}
function Card({ title }: CardProps) {
  return <h1>{title}</h1>
}

// ✅ Prefer — inline props type, `props.*` access
function Card(props: { title: string }) {
  return <h1>{props.title}</h1>
}
```

When the props type **is** shared, define it once (e.g. `export type CardProps = { ... }`) and still use `function Card(props: CardProps)` with `props.*`, not destructuring.
